      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1178">
               <p>John Jones, a native of <placeName>Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire</placeName>, was
                  one of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s most
                  scholarly lay helpers. He matriculated at Trinity College,
                     <placeName>Oxford</placeName> in <date when="1736">1736</date>, receiving his
                     <seg ana="degree">BA</seg> in <date when="1739">1739</date>, his <seg
                     ana="degree">MA</seg> in <date when="1742">1742</date>, and a <seg ana="degree"
                     >B.Med</seg>. in <date when="1745">1745</date> (by virtue of this last degree
                  he was known as Dr. Jones). Originally converted under <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>Whitefield</persName>, Jones gravitated to
                  the Arminianism of the Wesley brothers and began serving <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> as an assistant in
                     <placeName>London</placeName> in <date when="1746">1746</date>. In <date
                     when="1748">1748</date>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> appointed Jones
                  languages master at Kingswood School, and on <date when="1749-02-08">Feb. 8,
                     1749</date> solemnized Jones&apos;s marriage to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1352.xml"/>Elizabeth Mann</persName>. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1352.xml"/>Elizabeth</persName> died a year or two
                  later; and on <date when="1752-05-20">May 20, 1752</date> Jones was wed to
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1597.xml"/>Sarah Perrin</persName>.
                     <date when="1752">1752</date> capped a period of decline for Kingswood School
                  and by the end of that year Jones appears to have left his position. He remained
                  in <placeName>Bristol</placeName>, serving as <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s chief assistant for
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName> and <placeName>Cornwall</placeName>, and
                  boarding and tutoring some select students (including <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s nephew <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0912.xml"/>Westley Hall Jr</persName>. and
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0964.xml"/>Lady
                  Huntingdon</persName>&apos;s youngest son <persName>Henry</persName>. In <date
                     when="1758">1758</date> Jones left <placeName>Bristol</placeName>, but
                  continued a staunch friend of the Wesley brothers, listed as one of their chief
                  local preachers, moving to <placeName>London</placeName> to help care for the
                  society there (since he was too frail for <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerancy</seg>).
                  Because of his Methodist associations Jones&apos;s attempts to secure episcopal
                  ordination were long frustrated. In some exasperation, <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> helped arrange for Jones to be
                  ordained by <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0671.xml"/>Erasmus
                     Aulonita</persName>, who presented himself as Bishop of Arcadia. This
                  ordination proved controversial and in <date when="1770">1770</date> Jones finally
                  secured ordination from the Bishop of <placeName>London</placeName>. He ended his
                  days as vicar of <placeName>Harwich, Essex</placeName>. See <hi rend="italic"
                     >Alumni Oxonienses</hi>; Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 224; <hi
                     rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 621; Ives, <hi rend="italic">Kingswood</hi>, 24–25; A.
                  Barrett Sackett, <hi rend="italic">John Jones, First After the Wesleys?</hi>
                  (Bankhead Press, <date when="1972">1972</date>); and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 185.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
